    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "That's a good start for a summary, but some legal scholars argue that \"substantive due process\" is actually a bit of a legal fiction or even a way for judges to bypass the democratic process. How should I address those criticisms in my lesson so the students understand why it's such a controversial part of the Constitution?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Those critics are essentially arguing that judges are imposing their own personal moral views onto the Constitution, which is a dangerous form of judicial activism. The core of the debate is whether the Supreme Court is correctly interpreting the text or if it is simply substituting its own policy preferences for those of the elected legislature. To understand the controversy, students must recognize that the power to define fundamental rights is inherently political, even when cloaked in legal language.",
      "source": "target",
